    <name>
				<text>16.1.3.2 Write series in summation form</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Complete the summation form of the series \[ \sum_{p=1}^n = \dfrac{1}{1\times {@p_gap+1@}}+\dfrac{1}{2\times {@p_gap+2@}}+\dfrac{1}{3 \times {@p_gap+3@}}+\cdots+\dfrac{1}{{@n@}\times{@n+p_gap@}}\]below. Start by finding an expression for the typical term,
    “the \(p^{th}\) term” \(a_p\) and the determine the upper index \(n\).&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-size: 0.9375rem;">\(a_p=\) [[input:ans_sum]] [[validation:ans_sum]]</span></p>
<p>\(n=\) [[input:ans_upp]] [[validation:ans_upp]]</p><br>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>The summation index \(p\) is set to start from \(p=1\). Hence, the typical term must be given by \(\displaystyle {@ap@}\).</p>
<p>Then, the summation is written as \[\sum_{p=1}^{@n@} {@ap@}.\]</p><br>

<p>(<b>Note:</b> the question set \(p=1\) for the first term. This is a <b>choice</b>. If you start the summation at \(p=2\), then the upper bound is {@n+1@} and the typical term must be given by \(a_p = \dfrac{1}{(p-1)({@p+p_gap-1@})}\).)</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
